1 (a) The local transient lodging tax revenue that financed the debt shall be used as provided in
2 subsection (5) of this section; or
3 (b) The unit of local government shall thereafter eliminate the new tax or increase in tax oth-
4 erwise described in subsection (1) or (2) of this section.
5 (5) Subsections (1) and (2) of this section do not apply to a new or increased local transient
6 lodging tax if all of the net revenue from the new or increased tax, following reductions attributed
7 to collection reimbursement charges, is used consistently with subsection (6) of this section to:
8 (a) Fund tourism promotion or tourism-related facilities;
9 (b) Fund city or county services, whether emergency or nonemergency services, provided
10 directly by the city or county or by a special district in lieu of the city or county; or
11 (c) Finance or refinance the debt of tourism-related facilities and pay reasonable administrative
12 costs incurred in financing or refinancing that debt, provided that:
13 (A) The net revenue may be used for administrative costs only if the unit of local government
14 provides a collection reimbursement charge; and
15 (B) Upon retirement of the debt, the unit of local government reduces the tax by the amount
16 by which the tax was increased to finance or refinance the debt.
17 (6) At least [70] 40 percent of net revenue from a new or increased local transient lodging tax
18 shall be used for the purposes described in subsection (5)(a) or (c) of this section. No more than
19 [30] 60 percent of net revenue from a new or increased local transient lodging tax may be used for
20 the purpose described in subsection (5)(b) of this section.
21 (7)(a) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, a unit of local government may use
22 unexpended net revenue collected before the effective date of this 2026 Act from a new tax
23 described in subsection (1) of this section in accordance with subsection (6) of this section.
24 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (2) of this section, a unit of local government may use
25 unexpended net revenue collected before the effective date of this 2026 Act that is attribut-
26 able to the rate of the local transient lodging tax in effect on July 1, 2003, and to any increase
27 in the rate made on or after July 2, 2003, in accordance with subsection (6) of this section.
28 (c) Notwithstanding subsection (3) of this section, a unit of local government may, in
29 accordance with subsection (6) of this section, decrease the percentage of total local tran-
30 sient lodging tax revenues that are actually expended to fund tourism promotion or
31 tourism-related facilities regardless of when the percentage went into effect.
32 SECTION 2. The amendments to ORS 320.350 by section 1 of this 2026 Act become oper-
33 ative on January 1, 2027.
34 SECTION 3. The amendments to ORS 320.350 by section 1 of this 2026 Act apply to net
35 revenue collected by units of local government before, on or after the effective date of this
36 2026 Act.
37 SECTION 4. (1)(a) A unit of local government that imposes a local transient lodging tax
38 under ORS 320.345 to 320.365 shall file a biennial report with the Department of Revenue no
39 later than September 1 of each odd-numbered year, beginning in 2027.
40 (b) Upon request by one or more cities or counties, the League of Oregon Cities or the
41 Association of Oregon Counties, respectively, may file the report on behalf of the cities or
42 counties.
43 (2) The report must include the following information with respect to total transient
44 lodging tax revenue:
45 (a) For the preceding two fiscal years:
